{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01LtfrMZDNM2xbXGNapAJapY","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The backend was reloaded (at 12:19:53). But subsequent requests (from 12:20:30 onwards) are all returning 200. That means the rate limiting is being tracked but the burst is absorbing it.\n\nLooking at the nginx ingress rate limiting behavior:\n- `limit-rps: 1` sets the rate limit to 1 RPS\n- By default, the burst is `limit-burst-multiplier * limit-rps = 5 * 1 = 5`\n- So the first 5 requests within a second will be allowed (burst), then subsequent ones get 429\n- At 2 RPS with 0.5s sleep between requests, I'm sending 1 request every 500ms, which is 2 per second. The burst of 5 allows the first 5 requests to go through, but anything beyond that should hit the rate limit.\n\nLooking at the actual logs from 12:20:30 to 12:20:41, all 11 requests returned 200, even though the test only ran for 10 requests with 0.5s sleep (5 seconds total). This suggests the rate limiting isn't kicking in as expected—the burst is allowing everything through.\n\nI need to clarify how nginx's `limit_req` actually works. It uses a leaky bucket algorithm where `rate=1r/s` generates 1 token per second, and `burst=5` allows up to 5 tokens to accumulate. When requests arrive faster than the rate, they either get queued or rejected depending on whether `nodelay` is set.\n\nLooking at the nginx ingress controller configuration, it sets `limit-rps: 1` which translates to a rate limit of 1 request per second with a burst of 5 and nodelay enabled. But examining the test logs, the timestamps show requests spanning from 12:20:30 to 12:20:41—that's 11 seconds—which suggests the rate limiting might not be working as expected, so I should run a more aggressive test without delays between requests to see if it actually kicks in. I'm walking through the leaky bucket algorithm that nginx uses for rate limiting—with a burst of 5 and nodelay enabled, the first 6 requests should be served immediately, then subsequent requests get rejected once they exceed the 1 request per second rate.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":2352,"cache_read_input_tokens":36068,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":2352},"output_tokens":26,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"2f3d90bf-bf02-4058-8c8a-a72c447bb6a5","uuid":"6582d108-3aab-4f5a-af15-11622b477b12","request_id":"req_011CbyMb2ARkR6WUgizvxKrw"}
